  "text": "An informed voter always votes for the party whose policy, given the optimal leisure decision, yields maximum utility. The assumptions we make on the utility function imply that there exists a Condorcet winner among informed voters [CITATION_1] . In other words, both political parties converge to the preferred policy of the median informed voter. In equilibrium there may be some voters who, perfectly anticipating the platform proposed by political parties in the different states of the world, realize it is not acquiring information. Given the results in Proposition 1, we know that there is a threshold in the marginal productivity ( w) below which voters abstain.",
